SIMPLE: scorch
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scorch
<hw>Scorch</hw> <pr>(sk⟦ocir⟧rch)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Scorched</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Scorching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>scorchen</ets>, probably akin to <ets>scorcnen</ets>; cf. Norw.
<ets>skrokken</ets> shrunk up, <ets>skrekka</ets>,
<ets>skr⟦oum⟧kka</ets>, to shrink, to become wrinkled up, dial. Sw.
<ets>skr⟦aring⟧kkla</ets> to wrinkle (see <er>Shrug</er>); but perhaps
influenced by OF. <ets>escorchier</ets> to strip the bark from, to flay,
to skin, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧corcher</ets>, LL. <ets>excorticare</ets>; L.
<ets>ex</ets> from + <ets>cortex</ets>, <ets>-icis</ets>, bark (cf.
<er>Cork</er>); because the skin falls off when scorched.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To burn superficially; to parch, or shrivel, the
surface of, by heat; to subject to so much heat as changes color and
texture without consuming; <as>as, to <ex>scorch</ex>
linen</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Summer drouth or sing⟦egrave⟧d air⟦br⟧
Never <qex>scorch</qex> thy tresses fair.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To affect painfully with heat, or as with heat; to
dry up with heat; to affect as by heat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lashed by mad rage, and <qex>scorched</qex> by brutal fires.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To burn; to destroy by, or as by, fire.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Power was given unto him to <qex>scorch</qex> men with fire.</q>
<rj><qau>Rev. xvi. 8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The fire that <qex>scorches</qex> me to death.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scorch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scorch
<hw>Scorch</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be burnt on the
surface; to be parched; to be dried up.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Scatter a little mungy straw or fern amongst your seedlings, to
prevent the roots from <qex>scorching</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To burn or be burnt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He laid his long forefinger on the scarlet letter, which forthwith
seemed to <qex>scorch</qex> into Hester's breast, as if it had been red
hot.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To ride or drive at great, usually at excessive,
speed; -- applied chiefly to automobilists and bicyclists.
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></def> -- <wordforms><wf>Scorch"er</wf>,
<pos>n.</pos> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></wordforms></p>

<p><ent>scorcher</ent>⟦br⟧
